Epub  2015 Apr 14.

Truncated cross-sectional average length of life: A measure for comparing the 
mortality history of cohorts.

Canudas-Romo V(1), Guillot M.

Author information:
(1)a University of Southern Denmark.

Period life expectancies are commonly used to compare populations, but these 
correspond to simple juxtapositions of current mortality levels. In order to 
construct life expectancies for cohorts, a complete historical series of 
mortality rates is needed, and these are available for only a subset of 
developed countries. The truncated cross-sectional average length of life (TCAL) 
is a new measure that captures historical information about all cohorts present 
at a given moment and is not limited to countries with complete cohort mortality 
data. The value of TCAL depends on the rates used to complete the cohort series, 
but differences between TCALs of two populations remain similar irrespective of 
the data used to complete the cohort series. This result is illustrated by a 
comparison of TCALs for the US with those for Denmark, Japan, and other 
high-longevity countries. Specific cohorts that account for most of the 
disparity in mortality between the populations are identified.

DOI: 10.1080/00324728.2015.1019955
